,"1266":"1266","1275":"1275","before 1260":"before 1260","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","Andreas, Ayre, Isle of Man":"Andreas, Isle of Man","Salesbury, Blackburn, Lancashire, England":"Salesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salesbury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name primarily from Salesbury in Blackburn (Lancashire) but also occasionally from Salisbury (Wiltshire). The Lancashire placename derives from Old English <i>salh</i> ‘willow, sallow’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’, while the Wiltshire placename arises from a shortened form of the Celtic placename <i>Sorviodunum</i> (from an unknown initial element + Celtic <i>dūno-</i> ‘fort’). In the Old English period the second element was dropped and <i>Sorvio-</i> (of unexplained etymology) became <i>Searo-</i> in Old English as the result of folk etymological association the Old English word <i>searu</i> ‘trick’; to this an explanatory <i>burh</i> ‘fortress, manor, town’ was added. The city is recorded in the Domesday Book as <i>Sarisberie</i>; the change of <i>-r-</i> to <i>-l-</i> is the result of later dissimilation."],"variants":[{"name":"Saulsbury","meanings":["English: variant of   Salisbury  ."]},{"name":"Saulsberry","meanings":["Altered form of English   Salisbury  ."]},{"name":"Salsbery","meanings":["English: variant of   Salisbury  ."]},{"name":"Salsbury","meanings":["English (Worcestershire): variant of   Salisbury  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Salomon   or some other Jewish name beginning with <i>Sa-</i>."]},{"name":"Salsberry","meanings":["English: variant of   Salisbury  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354209,"age":25,"year":"1266","julianDay":2183458,"description":"The war between Scotland and Norway ends with the Treaty of Perth which transferred Mann to Scotland.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id"